<BaseLayout
  title="Thursday — Thor | Nazaryah"
  description="The day-name Thursday comes from Thor, the Norse god of thunder and storm. Here is who he was and why mapping his day onto Yahuah's calendar is a mistake."
>
  <article class="pg">
    <div class="pg-inner">

      <a href="/calendar" class="pg-back"><span class="arrow">←</span><span>Back to the Calendar</span></a>

      <header class="pg-header">
        <p class="pg-eyebrow">Thursday</p>
        <h1 class="pg-title">Thor</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Norse god of thunder, lightning, and storm</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        Every Thursday on the Gregorian calendar honors a Norse storm-god. His name was <strong>Thor</strong> (<em>Thunor</em> in Old English, <em>Donar</em> in Old German), and he was worshiped across the Germanic world as the god of thunder, lightning, and the protective might of the heavens.
      </p>

      <h2>Who He Was</h2>

      <p>
        Thor was the son of Odin (Woden) and one of the most popular gods of the Norse pantheon. He was associated with thunder — every thunderstorm was understood as Thor riding his goat-drawn chariot across the sky, swinging his hammer Mjölnir against the giants who threatened gods and men. His worshipers wore small hammer-pendants around their necks (Thor's hammer amulets are still made and sold today), and they called on him for protection in storms, in battle, and in childbirth.
      </p>

      <p>
        The Romans identified Thor with their chief god Jupiter — both wielded thunderbolts, both were sky-gods, both ruled over weather. The Roman day of Jupiter (<em>dies Jovis</em>) became the day of Thor in the Germanic adaptation. Old English <em>Þunresdæg</em> — "Thunor's day" — became Thursday. In Romance languages the day still carries Jupiter's Latin name: French <em>jeudi</em>, Italian <em>giovedì</em>, Spanish <em>jueves</em>.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        Crediting a storm-god for thunder and rain is the oldest pagan instinct. Yahuah Himself is the One who sends thunder, who bends the lightning, who pours the rain on the earth — and Scripture rebukes those who give that credit to anyone else.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Psalm 29:3</span> — "The voice of Yahuah is upon the waters: the Elohim of glory thundereth: Yahuah is upon many waters."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Job 37:2–5</span> — "Hear attentively the noise of his voice, and the sound that goeth out of his mouth. He directeth it under the whole heaven, and his lightning unto the ends of the earth… Elohim thundereth marvellously with his voice."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Jeremiah 14:22</span> — "Are there any among the vanities of the Gentiles that can cause rain? or can the heavens give showers? art not thou he, O Yahuah our Elohim?"
      </div>

      <p>
        Jeremiah's question is direct. Can any of the gods of the nations cause rain? Can the heavens give showers on their own? No. Only Yahuah does these things. Naming a day after a thunder-god gave Thor credit for what only the Creator could do — and worshipers of Thor explicitly attributed thunderstorms to his chariot crossing the sky. The credit was misplaced. The day-name preserves the misplacement.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Some will ask: <em>"What day in Yahuah's calendar is Thursday really?"</em> The question itself misunderstands the two systems.
      </p>

      <p>
        Thursday is a Roman day named after Jupiter, then renamed in the Germanic world after the Norse thunder-god. It belongs to Babylon's clock — the continuous seven-day rotation tied to pagan deities. Yahuah's clock does not have a Thursday. Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He hung in the heavens. The new moon is Day 1 of the month — a non-work day, though not a Sabbath. From there the days are numbered, and the Sabbaths fall on Days 8, 15, 22, and 29. When the next new moon appears, the count resets.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>There is no Thursday in this system.</strong> Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from the name of a thunder-god whose hammer the pagan world wore around its neck. The Roman week and Yahuah's reckoning are two different clocks, running on different principles, and they do not translate into each other.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        Knowing where the name "Thursday" came from does not necessarily mean a believer must stop saying it. But knowing the origin matters. The fifth day of the Roman week carries the name of a Norse god who was credited with what only Yahuah does. Every storm, every rain, every flash of lightning is His doing — not Thor's, not Jupiter's. The day-name on the calendar still gives the credit to a creature.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them what day it is. The world watches its phone and lets a thunder-god tell it what day it is. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        Thursday is Thor's day. The thunder he was credited with comes from the voice of Yahuah upon the waters — not from a hammer in the hand of a Norse god.
      </div>

